\begin_body

\begin_layout Section
Empirical Analysis
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Results"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section presents five main findings that apply to the periods under
 consideration: (i) effective inventors became more concentrated across
 economic sectors; (ii) sectors with increased product market concentration
 attracted a growing share of relevant inventor types; (iii) growth in the
 share of relevant inventors negatively correlated with inventor productivity,
 as measured by forward citations as well as average growth in output per
 worker divided by effective inventors employed; (iv) growth in the share
 of inventors coincided with increased concentration of inventors 
\emph on
within
\emph default
 sectors; and (v) growth in inventor shares are positively correlated with
 increases in patent enforcement cases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Results (i) and (ii) indicate a positive causal link between the growth
 in product market concentration and the increase in sectors' inventor share.
 Findings (iii), (iv) and (v) point to misallocation: Inventor concentration
 in less competitive sectors turns out to be inefficient, as researchers
 are predominantly employed on projects that do not contribute to the growth
 of the sector.
 This work amounts to defensive innovation, as evidenced by the decline
 in forward citations of patents obtained by these firms, the decrease in
 growth per inventor, and the increase in patent litigations that accompany
 the increase in product market concentration.
 I discuss the causal interpretation of my results through an IV specification
 in Subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:MainResults"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Variable Definitions and Main Specification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Key to my analysis are measures of inventor concentration and of R&D productivit
y.
 I rely on the definition of effective inventors, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

, explained in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:KnowledgeMarkets"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 For each product market 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, I define the share of inventors employed by the sector in year 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{Inventor\ Share}{}_{p,t}\equiv\frac{\sum_{p(i,t)=p}\alpha_{i}}{\sum_{k(i,t)=k}\alpha_{i}},
\]

\end_inset

where the numerator sums effective inventors in product market 
\begin_inset Formula $p,$
\end_inset

 and the denominator computes total effective inventors in the relevant
 knowledge market.
 I also use effective inventors 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

 to evaluate the dispersion of inventors across sectors.
 Results are robust to using raw counts of researchers instead of effective
 inventors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When analyzing R&D productivity I focus on two patent-based measures described
 in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Other data and aggregation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

â€”forward citations and patent generality.
 Further, I compute a more direct measure of the productivity of inventors
 as the growth in output per worker divided by the number of effective inventors
 employed by the sector.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In most specifications, the independent variables are measures of concentration
 and controls for the size of the sector considered.
 As discussed in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Data-Sources"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, my baseline measure of concentration is the lower bound of the Herfindal-Hirsc
hman Index constructed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "keilTroubleApproximatingIndustry2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, which I label 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{\text{HHI}}_{p,t}$
\end_inset

.
 I show below that the Economic Census HHI and its lower bound, when both
 available, produce equivalent results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I obtain measures of sales from the Economic Census, which I deflate using
 BLS NAICS-specific price indexes.
 I use sales variables for two purposes.
 First, real sales in 2012 are the weight in my regressions.
 Second, I use the logarithm real sales as well as a quartic in real sales
 to control for changes in the size of sectors during my sample period.
 For the selected subset of sectors that reports the number of companies,
 I show that my findings are robust to controlling for sales per company,
 a proxy for the average firm size.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I estimate a sector-level long-difference regression over the period 1997-2012
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta\text{Share}_{p,\ 2012-1997}=f_{k}\mathbf{1}\left\{ p\in k\right\} \ +\ \beta\Delta\underline{\text{HHI}}_{p,\ 2012-1997}\ +\ \gamma'\Delta\text{Size}_{p,\ 2012-1997}\ +\ \varepsilon_{p},\label{eq: spec}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\text{Share}$
\end_inset

 denotes the change in the inventors' share of product market 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{k}\mathbf{1}\left\{ p\in k\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a dummy variable that takes value 1 if the product market belongs to
 knowledge market 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\underline{\text{HHI}}$
\end_inset

 is the change in the HHI lower bound; and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\text{Size}$
\end_inset

 is a set of controls for the size of sector 
\emph on
p
\emph default
.
 Depending on the specification, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\text{Size}$
\end_inset

 is the change in log real sales, the change in log real sales per firm,
 or a quadratic polynomial in real sales changes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Regressions are weighted by sector sales in 2012 for the findings which
 rely on Economic Census sector-level measures, and I estimate robust standard
 errors in all specifications.
 When looking at patent measures, I employ the same specification as in
 equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: spec"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, where I replace the outcome variable with the change in patent productivity
 and the independent variable with the change in inventors' share.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
As I will show, the change in the inventor share is highly correlated with
 the change in the HHI, so this specification essentially amounts to a rescaling
 of the coefficient that would be obtained using the HHI.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In this case, since I do not rely on Economic Census measures, I report
 unweighted regressions.
 I discuss the robustness of these findings to using the HHI lower bound
 and weighting by sales.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Results
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:MainResults"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Inventor Concentration across NAICS Sectors has Increased
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Effective-inventor-HHI"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 reports the time series of inventor concentration across NAICS 4-digit
 industries for the period 1976-2016, for which the 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "goldschlagAlgorithmicLinksProbabilities2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 data is available.
 Panel (a) depicts the share of effective inventors and panel (b) that of
 raw inventors.
 I use the HHI index of inventor shares accruing to each sector as a measure
 of concentration.
 Both panels display an increasing concentration of inventors beginning
 in the late 1990s.
 The increase in inventor concentration is sizable, corresponding to about
 a 20% increase in the HHI for the effective inventor measure over the period
 1997-2012.
 Based on raw inventor data, the figure rises to 30%.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Effective-inventor-HHI"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 extends the findings in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "akcigitWhatHappenedBusiness2019a"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, who document a rising share of patents registered by top firms within
 sectors, to the cross-industry allocation of inventors.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A similar pattern emerges for concentration in specific CPC classes (available
 on request).
\end_layout

\end_inset

 As for the results presented below, the effective inventor measure and
 the raw inventor count behave similarly, although the figure for effective
 inventors is less volatile since this measure derives from a regression
 that residualizes time, firm, and technology class fixed effects.
\end_layout

