\begin_layout Subsubsection
Markets with Growing Concentration Increased Their Inventor Share
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, I present three sets of results for each specification,
 which differ in the estimation sample to account for extreme observations.
 In regression tables, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Full Sample
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 includes all non-missing observations for the variables considered.
 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Trim Outliers
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 sample drops the most extreme observations for the outcome and the independent
 variable.
 I exclude the observations that fall beyond three standard deviations from
 the sample average of each variable and that are most likely to drive the
 results estimated using the full sample.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
I justify the choices for each variable in detail in my replication code
 using the empirical kernel density and detailed tabulations.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Mahalanobis
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 sample excludes the 5% extreme observations based on the Mahalanobis distance
 of pairs of observations from the data centroid.
 This procedure is based on the joint distribution of outcomes and independent
 variables, which may result in a different sample for each regression.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float table
wide false
sideways false
status open

