\end_inset

 implies that 1pp increase in the share of inventors employed by a sector
 was associated with a highly significant increase of 3.6 litigation cases
 per 1000 patents.
 This compares to the average increase of 1.33 litigations per 1000 patents
 observed over the period.
 Alternatively, a one standard deviation increase in the share of inventors
 (3pp) raises litigations per 1000 patents by 11.8, which corresponds to
 0.5 standard deviations.
 The coefficients are virtually unchanged when size controls are included,
 outliers are dropped as above, or increases in inventor shares are lagged
 to mitigate concerns of reverse causality (results are available upon request).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This last set of results further supports the hypothesis that defensive
 innovation increased in concentrating sectors.
 To protect their dominant position, firms engage in such R&D to thwart
 innovation by potential competitors, which manifests through an increase
 in patent enforcement cases and a reduction in inventors' productivity
 in sectors with increased concentration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Discussion of Alternative Channels
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above analysis shows that inventors have accrued to sectors with increased
 concentration, primarily to incumbent firms, leading to an increase in
 litigation, a fall in inventors' productivity and forward citations.
 My interpretation of these empirical findings is that firms in high-concentrati
on sectors have increased their efforts in defensive innovation, meant to
 secure patents that can later be used to discourage further entry.
 However, other papers are also consistent with increased concentration
 of inventors within sectors and decreased R&D productivity.
 Two competing explanations stand out.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A first explanation may come from technological complexity in the spirit
 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "bloomAreIdeasGetting2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 While R&D might in general have become more difficult, my results do not
 show a decrease in patents per inventor in sectors with increased concentration.
 On the contrary, given that my inventor measure captures patent per capita,
 I effectively observe a relative increase in patenting activity in high-concent
ration sectors, excluding that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ideas getting harder to find
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 drive my results.
 Another explanation is increasing incremental, firm-specific R&D, as documented
 by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "akcigitSlowingBusinessDynamism2020,akcigitTenFactsDeclining2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 I verify that sectors with increased concentration did not see more self-citati
ons or falling patent generality, which are commonly used measures of the
 radical nature and applicability of patents.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "app: SelfCites"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Thus, incremental innovation does not appear to be driving my findings,
 which therefore document an independent channel lowering inventors' productivit
y.
\end_layout

\end_body
